properties.MATERIALS: Gravel and sand.  May include minor amounts of till.  Portions of many eskers below the marine limit are partly or entirely buried by glaciomarine deposits.
properties.TOPOGRAPHY: Individual or multiple ridges.  Complex eskers may have anastomosing patterns and be gradational with other types of ice-contact deposits.
properties.ORIGIN: Chiefly deposited by meltwater streams flowing in tunnels within or beneath the late Wisconsinan ice sheet.  Map unit also includes small undifferentiated areas of units "g" and "go".

properties.MATERIALS: Silt, clay, and minor amounts of gravel. Commonly a clayey silt (the Presumpscot Formation).  Sand is dominant in some places, but may be underlain by finer grained sediments. Locally fossiliferous. Map unit includes small areas of till and other units
properties.MATERIALS2: that are not completely covered by marine sediments.
properties.TOPOGRAPHY: Flat to gently sloping except where dissected by modern streams Commonly has a branching network of steep-walled stream gullies.
properties.ORIGIN: Composed of glacial sediments that accumulated on the ocean floor.  Formed during the late-glacial marine submergence of lowland areas in southern Maine.

properties.UNIT: Swamp, marsh, and bog deposits (includes both freshwater and saltwater marshes)
properties.MATERIALS: Peat, muck, clay, silt, and sand
properties.ORIGIN: Formed by accumulation of sediments and organic material in depressions and other poorly drained areas.

properties.MATERIALS: Heterogeneous mixture of sand, silt, clay, and stones.  May include many boulders.  Generally massive, but in many places contains beds and lenses of variably washed and stratified sediments.
properties.TOPOGRAPHY: Generally a blanket deposit that conforms to the underlying bedrock topography.  Also forms drumlins and other glacially streamlined hills.
